Here's an example of a Discord.js v14 command using slash commands:

```javascript
const Discord = require('discord.js');
const bot = new Discord.Client();

bot.on('message', async message => {
    if (message.content === '/ban') {
        const member = message.mentions.members.first();
        if (member) {
            await member.ban();
            message.reply('Banned successfully');
        } else {
            message.reply('You must mention a member to ban them');
        }
    }
});
```

Note that in this example, the command `/ban` is a slash command, which requires the user to use the slash character (`/`) before the command name to trigger it. The code checks if the message content contains `/ban`, and if it does, it retrieves the mentioned member and bans them if one is found. The code then sends a response to the user indicating that the ban was successful or noting that they must mention a member to ban them.

